DWARF debug information tests
=============================

These tests check the debug information emitted by "v3c -dwarf", which is
currently supported only for the x86-64-linux target. The point of the suite is
that source-level stepping and inspection actually work in gdb, so wherever
possible the assertions are made by gdb itself rather than by inspecting bytes.

Running
-------

    cd test/dwarf && ./test.bash              # all tests
    cd test/dwarf && ./test.bash lines.v3     # one test

The suite runs in three tiers, each skipped when its prerequisites are missing,
so it degrades gracefully on hosts that cannot run x86-64 Linux binaries:

  compile  Every *.v3 file compiles with -dwarf. Always runs.

  run      The compiled binary still behaves identically with debug info in it
           (*.v3.out and *.v3.exit hold the expected stdout and exit code).
           Needs a configured runner for x86-64-linux; see test/configure.

  gdb      gdb is pointed at the binary and its output is compared against a
           golden file. Needs $VIRGIL_LOC/test/config/gdb-x86-64-linux*, which
           test/configure links to a native gdb, or to one in a linux/amd64
           container when docker is available.

           static   *.static.gdb only inspects the debug info and never starts
                    the program, so it works even under emulation.

           run      *.run.gdb sets breakpoints, runs, steps and prints values.
                    This needs gdb to be able to ptrace the inferior, which
                    rules out emulated linux/amd64 containers (Rosetta and
                    qemu-user both fail). The suite probes for this and skips
                    the tier if the probe fails, so in practice these run on
                    native x86-64 Linux hosts and in CI.

Files per test
--------------

    foo.v3            the program
    foo.v3.out        expected stdout when run
    foo.v3.exit       expected exit code when run
    foo.static.gdb    gdb commands that do not run the program
    foo.static.out    expected (normalized) output of the above
    foo.run.gdb       gdb commands that run and step through the program
    foo.run.out       expected (normalized) output of the above

Writing tests
-------------

Addresses, build directories and gdb chatter are filtered out of gdb's output
before comparison (see normalize() in test.bash), so goldens stay stable across
machines and compiler changes.

The static goldens can be regenerated with ./gen.bash after reviewing the diff.

The *.run.gdb scripts deliberately do not depend on how gdb formats values.
They assert with gdb conditionals and print a fixed "ok: ..." line for each
assertion that holds, so the golden file is just the list of expected "ok"
lines and an assertion that fails simply drops a line from the output. Prefer
this style: it survives gdb version upgrades, and a failure names the property
that broke.

Remember that a script's breakpoints fire in program order. A breakpoint on
code that has already executed by the time an earlier breakpoint is hit will
never trigger, and the program will just run to completion.

Known gaps
----------

Things the emitter does not do yet, so that a test that "mysteriously" fails to
observe one of them is not mistaken for a regression:

  - Only x86-64-linux emits DWARF. Target.supportsDwarf gates this, so -dwarf
    is silently ignored on every other target rather than producing a broken or
    truncated .debug_info. arm64-linux, x86-linux and the Darwin (Mach-O) and
    Wasm targets all need their own work.

  - Parameters are described as DW_TAG_variable rather than
    DW_TAG_formal_parameter, so "info args" and the argument list in a frame
    header are empty even though the values are readable by name.

  - The location of an SSA-form local is only accurate from its definition to
    the end of its scope. Nothing tracks when the register holding it is reused
    for something else, so a local can still read back another value late in a
    method. Non-SSA locals (those assigned more than once) do get a full
    location list and are accurate throughout.

  - Variants are emitted as DW_TAG_unspecified_type; their cases and fields are
    invisible. Unboxed variants have no single location at all.

  - Components (and therefore global variables) are not described.

  - -dwarf turns off both local and global register allocation, so a binary
    built with debug info is slower and larger than a normal one: roughly 40%
    more code on test/dwarf/objects.v3. -dwarf-line does not, and emits line
    numbers only.

    Turning off LocalRegAlloc is also why every SSA local claims the same
    register in the goldens: the naive allocator reuses one register for
    everything, rather than the distinct registers a real allocation gives.

  - -dwarf at -O3 crashes the SSA verifier. Early inlining (InlineEarly, on at
    -O3) does not remap the inputs of SsaCheckpoint, leaving dataflow edges
    with a null destination. This predates the debug info work and reproduces
    with the stable compiler; -dwarf-line -O3 hits it too, -dwarf -O2 does not.
